Django ORM Predicates¶

Django: "The web framework for perfectionists with deadlines."

ORM (Object Relational Mapper): Maps a relational database onto Python objects. (django.db.models)

Predicate: "a statement that may be true or false depending on the values of its variables."

Title of the talk is "Django ORM predicates" Let's break that down

Django... "as you all know"

ORM... Also Rails' ActiveRecord, Java's Hibernate, etc.

Django ORM's goals (AFAICT)¶

  • Make database rows behave like python objects. ("object relational")
  • Make querysets behave like python containers (lists, sets), including logically. ("mapper")

AFAICT = As Far AS I Can Tell

Domain Specific language (DSL)¶

Domain-specific language (noun): a computer programming language of limited expressiveness focused on a particular domain.

— Martin Fowler

Examples: SQL, regular expressions, CSS, HTML, etc.

n/a

Django's ORM provides a DSL for constructing SQL queries.

Terminology¶

  • double__underscore__string=thing is a "lookup"
    • "Lookup" can also refer to __iexact, __in, etc.
  • QuerySet is an iterable container class for a SQL query

For the purposes of this talk.

"Lookup" seems to be an overloaded term in Django

if there's a better thing to call query components, let me know after the talk.

class Order(models.Model):
    pass

    order = models.OneToOneField(
        'app.InsuranceClaim')
    payer = models.ForeignKey(
        'app.InsurancePayer')
class InsurancePayer(models.Model):
    name = models.TextField()

Simple example from Counsyl: Patients place orders for genetic tests, which can be paid for by an insurance claim, which has a payer (e.g. "Blue Cross" or "Aetna")

In [36]:
import sqlparse
def pprint_sql(queryset):
    sql = str(queryset.only('pk').query)
    print(sqlparse.format(sql, reindent=True))

Helper function using the sqlparse library to nicely format SQL queries.

Protip: querysets have a .query attribute which can be cast to a string to get the raw SQL.

Very useful for debugging the ORM.

SELECT "app_order"."id"
FROM "app_order"
INNER JOIN "app_insuranceclaim" ON ("app_order"."id" = "app_insuranceclaim"."order_id")
INNER JOIN "app_insurancepayer" ON ("app_insuranceclaim"."payer_id" = "app_insurancepayer"."id")
WHERE "app_insurancepayer"."name" = Aetna

Two joins: order to insurance claim to insurance payer, filters to orders whose claim's payer's name is "Aetna".

Subtlety: Lookups are trees.¶

MyModel.objects.filter(
    foo__bar__attr1=1,
    foo__bar__attr2=2,
    foo__baz__attr3=3)

A useful way to think of how the ORM evaluates queries.

The ORM will form a single join for the bar relation, and have two clauses in the WHERE statement.

Does not quite work that way for .exclude() queries.

Django's query DSL is good.¶

  • It's simple. ("Two underscores between related things.")
  • Much easier to use than SQL. Very concise.
  • Works pretty well in practice.

Like most successful DSLs, this is probably a combination of luck & skill.

Warts¶

  • Weird semantics on joins.
  • Confusing casting semantics.
  • Weird hodgepodge like `__week_day` lookup.
  • Casting around date and time

django.db.models.Q objects¶

some_queryset.filter(foo=1, bar=2)

is equivalent to either:

some_queryset.filter(Q(foo=1) & Q(bar=2))
some_queryset.filter(Q(foo=1, bar=2))

n/a

django.db.models.Q objects¶

some_queryset.exclude(foo=1)

is equivalent to:

some_queryset.filter(~Q(foo=1))

n/a

Boolean operations¶

  • Q(foo=1) & Q(bar=2) (Conjunction / "and")
  • Q(foo=1) | Q(bar=2) (Disjunction / "or")
  • ~Q(foo=1) (Negation / "not")

So Q objects are Boolean expression trees of logical predicates.

Break it down:

  • Boolean (True or False)
  • Expression Tree (like an abstract syntax tree, where the nodes are connectors or lookups).
  • Predicates: Something that can be true or false. "The payer's name is Aetna" from earlier.

Q objects are good for:¶

  • Code reuse (use the same query in different places).
  • Literate variable names:
has_high_risk_indicator = Q(
    indications__risk_level="HIGH")
has_twin_pregnancy = Q(pregnancy__count__gte=2)
is_covered_Q = has_high_risk_indicator & ~has_twin_pregnancy
def get_covered_people_for_processing():
    return Person.objects.filter(is_covered_Q,
                                 status='UNPROCESSED')

One of the tests we perform at Counsyl is only reimbursed by insurance in some circumstances:

  • Some risk indicator like an abnormal ultrasound.
  • Validation trials exist showing it works (not done for twin or triplet pregnancies, etc.)

We can use Q objects to make code more comprehensible, or reuse parts of a query, like checking for a high risk indication.

Q objects¶

👍 Q objects are useful. Use them. 👍

Q objects still suck¶

They require database round trips or code duplication to examine individual records.

Slow but DRY¶

def is_person_covered_SLOW(person):
      return (Person.objects
              .filter(is_covered_Q, id=person.id)
              .exists())

Define DRY: Don't Repeat Yourself

The database is slow¶

counsyl_product=> SELECT 1 FROM order_order LIMIT 1;
 ?column? 
----------
        1
(1 row)

Time: 0.703 ms

Actual example from a production database. All that's measured here is:

  • Query parsing.
  • Network latency.
  • Checking whether the table has at least one row.

700 microseconds is a lot of microseconds. Queries add up!

Code Duplication¶

def is_person_covered_WET(person):
    has_high_risk_indicator = any(
        ind.risk_level == "HIGH"
        for ind in person.indications.all())
    has_twin_pregnancy = person.pregnancy.number >= 2
    return (has_high_risk_indicator
            and has_twin_pregnancy)

WET = not DRY (ha ha)

Notice the bug?

Code duplication leads to bugs¶

def is_person_covered_WET(person):
    has_high_risk_indicator = any(
        ind.risk_level == "HIGH"
        for ind in person.indications.all())
    has_twin_pregnancy = person.pregnancy.number >= 2
    return (has_high_risk_indicator and
            not has_twin_pregnancy)

Should be does not have a twin pregnancy. You need to fix it in multiple places every time something changes, etc.

Boolean expression trees of logical predicates¶

Earlier we say Q objects are..

Can't Python do that? Python is good at stuff.

Enter django-predicate¶

  • Developed by Preston Holmes (@ptone), https://github.com/django-predicate/django-predicate
  • Defines P which is Pretty much exactly™ like Q
    but with __contains__, eval and filter.
  • pip install django-predicate

P for Predicate, Q for query

Predicate (P) objects¶

  • P subclasses Q, so you can use it in querysets.
  • Acts like a container class: obj in P(foo=bar)
  • Also P(foo=bar).eval(obj)
  • Also work on nested dicts & ordinary Python objects.

n/a

Example¶

from predicate import P
has_high_risk_indicator = P(
    indications__risk_level="HIGH")
has_twin_pregnancy = P(pregnancy__count__gte=2)
is_covered_P = has_high_risk_indicator & ~has_twin_pregnancy
def is_person_covered_DRY_and_FAST(person):
    return person in is_covered_P

covered_people = Person.objects.filter(is_covered_P)

n/a

Example application:
Record linkage

We get the equivalent of Explanations of Benefits back from insurers. Sometimes the data doesn't quite match our patient records (e.g. due to a name change or typo).

We want to automatically match as many as possible, and provide informative view of possible matches for manual resolution in a queue.

Example application:
Record Linkage

Task: EOB matching to our database.

  • Algorithm: Apply a ranked series of match queries, accepting the first to match.
  • e.g. match on first name, last name, member ID, date of service.
  • Nonmatches to a manual queue.
  • Problem: Querying the database is AND. Fixing nonmatches is OR.

n/a

n/a

PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES = r'[\s!"#$%&\'()*+,\-./:;<=>?\[\\\]^_`~]'
PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES_RE = re.compile(PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES)
REPEATED_PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES = '%s*' % PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES

def convert_name_to_fuzzy_regex_string(name):
    name = PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES_RE.sub('', name)
    name_with_arbitrary_punctuation = REPEATED_PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES.join(
        name) + REPEATED_PUNCTUATION_AND_SPACES
    return '^%s$' % name_with_arbitrary_punctuation

Finding bugs¶

  • Parameterized test suite across:
    • database backends
    • Django versions
    • Use tox, detox, tox-travis and travis-ci.org
  • Found bugs with Django 1.8 & sqlite

Tox: sets up parameterized test suites across any variable you want.

Detox: parallel tox

tox-travis: makes tox and travis work together

Travis: free countinuous integration for public projects.

Finding bugs¶

  • Find an invariant and test for it.
class OrmP(P):
    def eval(self, instance):
        manager = type(instance)._default_manager
        orm_value = manager.filter(self, pk=instance.pk).exists()
        super_value = original_eval(self, instance)
        assert_equal(orm_value, super_value)
        return super_value

Bugs¶

  • Multiple conditions on the same join didn't work right.
  • Reverse relations not handled right.
  • Negation was unhandled.

n/a

de Morgan's Laws¶

~(p & q) = ~p | ~q
~(p | q) = ~p & ~q

the negation of a disjunction is the conjunction of the negations;

the negation of a conjunction is the disjunction of the negations;

Basic component of classical logic

Proof by python¶

>>> from itertools import product
>>> bools = [True, False]
>>> all((not (p and q)) == (not p or not q)
...     for p, q in product(bools, bools))
True
>>> all((not (p or q)) == (not p and not q)
...     for p, q in product(bools, bools))
True

de Morgan's Laws violation¶

Django and logic don't see eye to eye on this stuff.

class Node(models.Model):
    m2m = models.ManyToManyField('self', related_name='reverse_m2m')
    attr1 = models.TextField()
    attr2 = models.TextField()
In [38]:
root = Node.objects.create()
root.m2m.create(attr1='foo', attr2='foo')
root.m2m.create(attr1='bar', attr2='bar')
q = Q(m2m__attr1='foo') & Q(m2m__attr2='bar')
q_double_negative = ~(~(Q(m2m__attr1='foo') & Q(m2m__attr2='bar')))
q_de_morgan = ~(~Q(m2m__attr1='foo') | ~Q(m2m__attr2='bar'))
In [39]:
print(Node.objects.filter(q))
print(Node.objects.filter(q_double_negative))
print(Node.objects.filter(q_de_morgan))

from predicate import P
nodes = Node.objects.all()
p = P(m2m__attr1='foo') & P(m2m__attr2='bar')
p_double_negative = ~(~(P(m2m__attr1='foo') & P(m2m__attr2='bar')))
p_de_morgan = ~(~P(m2m__attr1='foo') | ~P(m2m__attr2='bar'))
print(p.filter(nodes))
print(p_double_negative.filter(nodes))
print(p_de_morgan.filter(nodes))  # This was hard.

de Morgan's Laws violation¶

In [41]:
pprint_sql(Node.objects.filter(Q(m2m__attr1='foo') & Q(m2m__attr2='bar')))

SELECT "app_node"."id"
FROM "app_node"
INNER JOIN "app_node_m2m" ON ("app_node"."id" = "app_node_m2m"."from_node_id")
INNER JOIN "app_node" T3 ON ("app_node_m2m"."to_node_id" = T3."id")
WHERE (T3."attr1" = foo
       AND T3."attr2" = bar)

& requires conditions to be jointly satisfied on the same database row.

class Node(models.Model):
    m2m = models.ManyToManyField('self', related_name='reverse_m2m')
    attr1 = models.TextField()
    attr2 = models.TextField()
In [42]:
pprint_sql(Node.objects.filter(~(~Q(m2m__attr1='foo') | ~Q(m2m__attr2='bar'))))

SELECT "app_node"."id"
FROM "app_node"
WHERE NOT ((NOT ("app_node"."id" IN
                   (SELECT U1."from_node_id" AS Col1
                    FROM "app_node_m2m" U1
                    INNER JOIN "app_node" U2 ON (U1."to_node_id" = U2."id")
                    WHERE U2."attr1" = foo))
            OR NOT ("app_node"."id" IN
                      (SELECT U1."from_node_id" AS Col1
                       FROM "app_node_m2m" U1
                       INNER JOIN "app_node" U2 ON (U1."to_node_id" = U2."id")
                       WHERE U2."attr2" = bar))))

After passing through double negation, there needs to be at least one row satisfying each condition. (Weaker condition.)

  • Add support for F objects and custom lookups.
